Duel to the death: MP3 players versus cell phones
We'll advise you on how to choose
While almost every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
This clearly shows that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons for getting a self-help reader.
The choice depends entirely on the use and needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
Firstly, these music products are not released as LP and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
But if you have hard rock, jazz, blues vinyls on your shelves, you probably dream of a record player like that.
It also works with portable music, which is music that is compressed or simply in MP3 format.
Here too, there are categories of price and quality.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to digest the 20 crown headphones on the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
There's a lot to choose from.
It's the battery life that counts.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than simply read music, but that is not something that cell phones do even by accident.
There is no other device today as universal as the mobile phone.
Besides the primary functions of calling and texting, it can read music and video, record both, and it has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse, and maybe it can even surf.
And if you take smartphones and handhelds into account, you'll also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle because no refrigerator can make the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your cell phone, the sooner the indicator on the screen will ask for the charger.
And reading music takes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than 12 hours, usually, and much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simpler ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap cell phones, do not count on them lasting more than a few hours.
If you still occasionally make a few calls, get another charger at work for safety, even for the most expensive appliances.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least nine hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly onto the memory card, but few memory readers can do without a mini-card adapter that is not used in cell phones.
Readers, with a few exceptions (iPods) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players create a multimedia library of their own, sorted by artist name, album name, genre, or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, cell phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, you should be especially concerned with battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output, and clearly ease of use.
If you need music mainly as background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you need just any mobile phone that plays MP3.
Now, that's obviously on any cell phone.
You don't have to worry too much about what formats your cell phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support all of them, so the global majority of music that comes to you will be in this very format.
In addition to this format, which is among the most common, the vast majority of devices support music in WMA format.
The AAC format used by Apple and its iPods is less common.
The better cell phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Simply visit the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) via the mobile internet network and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile phone reader.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is meagre and usually limited to the hits of the radio moment.
The prices aren't really that low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (either via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones with them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something, they can go through their pockets while their MP3 player is left at home.
But it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your wireless earpiece.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small fraction of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the greatest advantage of mobile phone readers is, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you can buy a very decent walkman.
Usually, though, you'll be limited by the absence of an entry for common headphones.
The best and technically most equipped mobile phones, even with a 3.5 mm jack for ordinary headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
The advantage of the readers is, among other things, their easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) and can be handled by anyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally triggering the start-up of the mobile internet network and consequently a huge data bill.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, etc.).
The purchase of the respective card is also included in the 2 000 crowns.
But be careful.
The base models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the more expensive ones can even handle 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a cell phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, you can get Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are a demanding listener, you may want to pick up a specialized mobile phone - a walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual MP3 keys and the convenience of the service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
In this area, Sony Ericsson has made more progress, as the mobile phones in the Walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above brands provide the same service and price category up to 4 000 SEK, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, in principle up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe I did .
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all the services of their Western European partners.
However, something is missing here  a virtual operator that forces traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be gone long.
We have already written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
In the end, ČTÚ confirmed this, noting that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges may create a paradoxical situation - for some Czech mobile phone customers, SMS will be cheaper abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to start the fight.
This may sound absurd, but here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has often stressed this, having said in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities.
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the market led to a significant price decrease, which would have had to be met by traditional operators.
At the same time, even before the arrival of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in Britain.
But it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
In the end, we don't have to go very far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, to which U:fon belongs in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In other words, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional operator to operate effectively.
They do not entail relatively high costs for setting up, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
So in the world of virtual operators they usually come in low cost, offer low cost calls and SMS, which is often balanced with the more restricted service offerings.
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that costs at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even betting on a target group can be a pretty good move.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operators they like and trust", says David Seibertz CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be applied here as in Poland.
The Commission notes that the Czech Republic has not yet adopted a decision on the compatibility of the aid with the internal market.
In addition, from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated".
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there ever is an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk of expanding this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic are not very hopeful.
The start-up of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our region", Jana Studničková, the press spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation with Mobile.cz.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very favourable to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, it has been keen to launch a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them", says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
So maybe better times are coming.
We're getting unofficial reports that the first virtual operator should be here by the end of the year.
But for now, an impenetrable wall of silence stands around his creation.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no one with a complex and serious project has approached us", said Vlastimil Sršeň of Telefónica O2's press office in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificities of the Czech market are also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far we have not noticed any vital and mutually beneficial commercial project on which it is possible to continue to build".
He adds: "It is unlikely that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network before the end of the year.
We should have had a concrete agreement on the table by now, so that it could be considered on the horizon.'
Vodafone is focusing its attention rather on meeting its 3G licence requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for high-speed mobile internet.'
Competent authorities - with accomplices
The attitude of the mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The troubles surrounding the creation of U:fon testify that when operators care about something they know how to row in the same direction.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing on ČTÚ in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from ČTÚ's web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been further enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on it and especially on its services.'
The attitude of mobile operators is, however, quite surprising given the complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not just the attitude of the CTU that is at issue, unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - it has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That is the exclusive responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
'The virtual operator would be able to enter the mobile telephony market after the necessary infrastructure lease agreement between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer from potential buyers was probably not attractive enough for traditional operators,' said Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS External Relations Section, in response to our question.
This statement by the operators' representatives is perhaps not surprising.
But the fact that the Office must defend the interests of consumers and also ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators are commonly operating, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services".
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices are not in ÚOHS' interests.
What is really shocking about the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence, it arises by itself.
The same price for petrol for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competition.
'The Chamber has found no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position and therefore no correspondingly greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The telecommunications regulator may also lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile network market to virtual operators", Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many controversial issues .
There is of course the relevant market analysis by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different approach - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has - logically - a monopoly on its network.
So for a certain portion, it has to be dominant.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least alarming to ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the above-mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all operators.
To shift responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly common trick with which ÚOHS keeps itself out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not until the recently adopted update of the Telecommunications Act that the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was promoted, despite the fact that many experts expected this to improve the situation.
The representatives of ÚOHS must know this well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
You can do it when no one's looking.
We are not aware of the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of which even exist on Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephony services, but these are only partially public.
Usually these are companies that deal with multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the people who are pre-selected.
The magic is that the company is seen by the operator as a typical business customer, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, you then receive special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
'If the cases you are talking about, which we will be looking into, did occur, it could be a breach of contract and could lead to the termination of cooperation with this company,' Martina Kemrová answered the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity would not reach the ears of the operators responsible for mobile telephony.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time against such an attitude.
The Commission has already made a number of recommendations to the Council on the application of the principle of subsidiarity.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully use it as regular customers of mobile operators.
But that should be the least of the oddities at the CTU.
In addition, another question is raised for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators are blind to this attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It must be added that ÚOHS has a strong enough right to expose similar activities and if it does not want to, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and whose commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not expensive anymore
As has been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a significant decrease in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small a market, too saturated at the border, problems with quality of service, etc.
But in developed countries, it is precisely in these cases that regulators have stepped in to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created and others joined him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case at each other like a boiling potato.
In our experience we cannot escape the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes them more than comfortable.
But we're not giving up.
If the information from the backstage is correct and the virtual operator will appear very soon, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on track.
If one operator had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, ÚOHS could hardly remain unmoved by the refusal (discrimination) of the other operators concerned.
And maybe we'll stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On the occasion of the Czech Statehood Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on Sunday solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available  solo with male or female voice, choral step and instrumental edition.
The singing is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the website iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem one of the most beautiful hymns.
He told the radio station "Český rozhlas" earlier that he specifically chose to sing the solo variants, singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to make sure that both of them and the choir had clear diction, that the text was understandable, that they were in harmony", he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroupa.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously embraced it.
The first stanza of the song after the foundation of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
