MHD Prague Wednesday will also accompany you for the first time with an electronic card
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, tram and buses, who will have an electronic card in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
Right now , about 100,000 people can get it with their own Opencard .
Passengers can buy the 30- and 90-day and annual (valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have their card reloaded at the Infopoints and the offices of the Transport Company and at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stops.
The vouchers can be purchased online from yesterday at the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 customers had taken advantage of the service by the afternoon.
Those who start using the service via the internet can completely forget about the desks at the metro stops where they had to wait in long lines for paper tickets.
The voucher is purchased online and is recharged on the Opencard at one of the twelve branches of the Municipal Library.
"At these places, passengers have a trained desk that will help them with their online purchases and will also record the credit they have acquired on their card", said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic vouchers to Opencards at ATMs and self-service machines that are installed at the entrances to the metro.
What are these ATMs like?
They are red, resemble ticket wipers, and passengers have already noticed them at the metro stops Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the whole city but by the end of the year there should be 80", concluded Opatrný.
The receipt will be checked by the ATM instead of the driver.
The ATM service that will be operational from tomorrow is very simple.
Just insert the Opencard card and after you pay the coupon, it will load on top.
The electronic cards will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the urban lines of trains and buses numbered 300 to 499, which residents of the municipalities of central Bohemia take to reach the capital.
"On trains added to Prague's integrated transport, there are controllers with card readers to check the time and zone validity", explained Filip, a ticket controller from the organisation Ropid, which sets the timetables for Prague's public transport.
City buses have card readers built into the driver's trunk.
During the climb it is therefore necessary not only to show the magnetic card to the driver, but also to rest the Opencard on the point determined next to the cash register.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the loaded coupons.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the loaded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this kind of information", Drápal added.
Passengers who take city buses and will not remember when the voucher expires can go back to the self-service ATMs, where the vouchers are loaded onto paper.
Here information on the validity of their documents will be displayed on the device's screen.
Sudeten Germans wanted a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 asked to include Šumava in the United States.
This is stated in the letter deposited in the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States.
It is with this desire, it is said, that groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is shown above all by the letter kept in a private archive and now deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in the letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Sumava district"  occupied by Hitler under the Munich Agreement  to Czechoslovakia again.
"We understand the situation and want to be sure of the promises that American units will come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter signed with the words "The people who care about the fate of Šumava with all their heart" reads.
Since, they say, annexation by Czechoslovakia - knowing the Czech national character - gives the Sudeten Germans only hope of brutality, lack of consideration, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the letter's authors beg the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava now and forever.
"We cannot believe that without regard for the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would recognize this territory as a state alien to us, which oppresses and eradicates ethnic minorities and has contributed nothing, absolutely nothing, to the Allied victory", the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign it is the alleged fear of revenge from the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president were to doubt the conviction of the Germans in Šumava, all he would need to do is hold a referendum in the district on whether its inhabitants want to become part of the US or live under US rule.
