The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California studies and senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School".
Really attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama's education projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama's campaign notes that, "African American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students, "which is true.
To address these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama's education plan specifically supports, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for English students.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in classrooms in languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The students at the school are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, a surprising 100 percent of students passed the top-level test in the 2008 state math exam.
Equally astonishingly, 93 percent of fourth graders passed the English Language Arts Proficiency Test.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient from the one Mr. Obama preferred.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and practice, constant evaluation of skills and a no-excuse attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, the manager of Sixth Street, the school's obstructive approach to English students is "full immersion".
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Mrs. Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, said to me, "We had a fantastic success with a student who just came from Mexico, and if you walked into the classroom 12 months later, you wouldn't be able to tell which one it was".
"It works", he observed, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model to replicate in other schools with a majority of Hispanic and English students?
The school's achievements make the answer to that question very easy, but the education policy in his own party (the National Education Associations is a longtime supporter of bilingual education) and his own continued support for bilingual education prevent Mr. Obama's answer from being predictable.
While he agrees that immigrants should learn English, Obama recently trivialized the topic when he said that people should stop worrying about "English-only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "you must make sure your children are able to speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should be looking at the educational models that work rather than dismissing or trivializing them.
