Gebrselassie rested beats his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia has once again shown why many consider him the greatest marathon runner of all time, breaking his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2 mile race in under 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a win on the favourably flat race in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shattered his previous mark of 2:03:26 from last year's Berlin race by 27 seconds.
At 35, Gebrselassie sets the 26th world record in a career so stunning that it has produced a world championship or world record at every distance from the mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympics marathon, fearing - perhaps too alarmingly in retrospect - that air pollution would worsen her asthma problems.
Instead, he decided to run to Berlin.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won Sunday with a scorching average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As soon as half of runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya went long distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decades, since Ronaldo of the Brazilian Coast won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's win, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had cramps in his calves and missed a week of training.
Clearly, the rest has left him fresh, not rusty.
"I'm so happy", Gebrselassie told reporters in the newsroom.
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago, and I had some doubts today, but in the end everything went well".
He has been somewhat criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for over-orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars, relying on the open runway as if it were a half-finish race, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But these criticisms rarely diminish the greatness of Gebrselassie's skills as a marathon runner.
With the pace of four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie reached the halfway point in 1:02:04.
Two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, kept Gebrselassie in the race after the runway was cleared.
Just over three miles from the finish, Gebrselassie made a final climb to separate himself from Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi came in third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, completed a remarkable year by winning in 2:19:19, the seventh fastest time ever.
Paula Radcliffe of Great Britain holds the world record of 2:15:25.
Last spring, Mikitenko, 36, was a surprise winner of the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games with what is being described as a bad accident, but recovered to win in Berlin, setting her personal best time of almost five minutes in the third marathon she ran.
She ran a race with good math, letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners start with a big gap, picking it up after about 18 and a half miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
In a city apart, pride and trials of a black life
Tucked away in the sprawling theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, just a few miles from the glamour, the noise, the enormity, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into being.
Eatonville, the first all-black incorporated city in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city he described - and which makes tourists stop by including it in the Depression-era Florida tour guide produced by the Federal Writers' Project - remains a place apart.
It's as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little about us, doesn't know what he's missing".
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called to give an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very careful about how our story is told", said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It has to be right".
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It's both a historic pattern of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It's a literary center but also an example in the shade of oak trees of the rural black culture of the South -- sometimes despised, sometimes awarded -- born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through heartfelt, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida's guidebook transformed the town, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida into a backdrop of black history and human drama.
Low as a houseboat in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted them to more private areas.
"Outside the street on the left", he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white trim, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could barely read and write".
She also mentioned the new husband of the widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the hallways".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
Clearly, this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora told it like it was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalizes, quoting men who sing crude songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it".
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family's move to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston stormed into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others grinned.
"People were always very glad to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
But, he added, rocking in her chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no great memorial services, and no great conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A change occurred in the 1980's.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane freeway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the western edge of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the community's relative idyllic isolation.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white kids came and threw oranges and stuff at people sitting on one side", says Mr. Franklin.
"We actually had a girl who got killed by that once.
They threw a watermelon out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston petitioned the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown v. Board of Education "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that desegregation of schools, while positive in some respects, dilutes the cohesion of Eatonville and jeopardizes the confidence of its youth.
"Black kids used to be hugged - I remember this - you hug your teacher in the morning, you hug your teacher in the evening", said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher... - I mean, there's a cultural divide there", said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and made room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - a black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-assurance and lines like, "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long walk to Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing her into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter was back in the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state withdrew from its road project.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway, have brought what you would call high speed, a real pride for the city", Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project helped change the city's image of itself.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story bookstore (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a back street in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for the history of Eatonville, for its significance, are often still treated with caution.
A prior permission is required for most interviews, some things - like the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a chubby schoolteacher with a soft spot for bright red, still fear their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet as the Hurston Festival expanded, so did a high level of civic pride.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his whole race: beautiful, troubled and all, neither better nor worse and proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and confused as other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in local government or for the Police Department, who he said might need help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Many people, if they just walked in here, will think, 'Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon after the mass on a recent Sunday.
"But if you really stop and take a moment to look at the history, it's a really pretty town".
Here in New York we all speak fluently of finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they would not notice they were in the eye of the storm.
They would never guess that the glass offices, beehives over their heads the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York are having their worst "bad day at the office" every day since the 1929 crash.
Couriers shake metal tea carts across sidewalks, carrying trays of muffins for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet through apartment buildings carrying, like human mules, 50 broken stretched shirts hanging from a stick on their shoulders.
Employees still wait in line for their morning bagels at the food trucks on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to catch a yellow taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a workday.
It didn't seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had planned the event to coincide with my late afternoon break at my JPMorgan Chase branch, a line of about 20 was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier's desk to withdraw money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask directions to Macy's department store and new customers open accounts.
Many of the people in front of me, I would later learn from Starr, my "trusted banker", were in line for the same reason.
Unlike me, however, they've already taken savings from smaller banks from places they commute from, like those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have taken money from so-called thrift (a bit like a building society), credit unions and types of city savings banks whose branches only operate within a state, and they say they treat customers like family.
In the past few years, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, was placed into receivership, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings deposits, was looking for a buyer to bail it out.
The employees and salespeople who were standing in front of me, afraid of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank that was perceived as a safe haven, the bank that was asking for more collateral from Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers in the last few weeks have become financially competent.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld as if they were familiar, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed doorwoman, almost 50, from my apartment building, changed the subject from our usual conversation about Brad and Angelina or my grocery delivery.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, "Now I have all my savings in market funds!.
I'm not taking any chances".
