Heinz-Christian Strache, left of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party, take part in a demonstration to present the organization "City against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs like those road signs representing mosques with a red line running through the middle.
Police blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties gained a big lead in the national general election.
More than 90 graves were badly damaged at the Traun cemetery near Linz in the hours between Friday night and this morning, in what police believe was an organized action.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols like the Star of David on some of the graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask extremist motivations driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It's not clear if the incident is connected to the election in any way.
A spokesman for the local Muslim community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration, which occurred towards the end of Ramadan, a month of religious significance for Muslims.
Austria, meanwhile, has embarked on a journey of spiritual searching following its turn to the right in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that took almost 30 percent of the vote, the Austrian Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned with strongly anti-immigration ticket and some of their slogans were defined by xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party that won more than 18 percent of the vote, has campaigned against veils and burqas and has also expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be connected to Islam.
At the final rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties seem to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, claiming that they are political symbols of a continuing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses made immediately after the election, which established the far right as the strongest political bloc in the nation, indicate that change was being driven predominantly by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
