"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no flyers, no clothes from before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the performance, to look at the appearance of relaxed man or woman.
On one side, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two faces inseparable, except in private, in those moments away from the audience, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they don't have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots with singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this objective, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different viewing angles.
The exhibition, included in the program of the month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, which is growing every day", explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be about ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists who can convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capture the audience.
To capture the personalities of these great men, you don't have to portray them on stage.
Because their personality and character are inner.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with my camera the personalities of the great flamenco players".
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, because of the type of machine and the material, are reminiscent of classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day".
Not the dancing, singing or playing itself, but the artist's personality, his character, able to capture the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited at the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" (SportARTproject).
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits, "I love to portray people, get to know them and be able to penetrate for a moment into their lives, whether it's a long moment or a short one.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters you sometimes don't even know or who only give you a few minutes to take a picture.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
The collection of contemporary flamenco portraits, entitled "Flamenco-people", is on display at the El Fotómata gallery, at 20 via de la Mata, parallel to Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa reveals that the novel he is writing is a "joke"
It is set in places he does not yet know and deals with unknown topics: despite this, Mario Vargas Llosa is struggling with a new project he is working on, a novel whose protagonist, Roger Casemant, is an Irish nationalist who lived for twenty years in the Congo and crossed the Amazon.
The writer, who has always been favored for the Nobel Prize for Literature, admitted yesterday at the Hay Festival in Segovia that the project he is working on today "is a gamble" and that "everything indicates that I should not write it".
"If I had good sense, I wouldn't write it, but I will do it anyway and I hope to finish it as soon as possible", he concluded his speech at the festival for the exchange of ideas, thoughts and words that for four days saw a hundred writers, historians, journalists and thousands of people pass through the city of Aqueducts.
The author of "La ciudad y los perros" was, as expected, the leading figure at the third edition of the festival of the word.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival prize for being the most voted writer by the participants  an old edition of Dickens' book "Our mutual friend", filled the seats at the Juan Bravo theatre.
Presented by Félix Romeo, the writer found himself in front of a crowd whose time flew by when the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and great dose of humor, recalled how his literary vocation was born, derived from the "extraordinary adventure" of the "pleasure of reading" and "living beyond what I lived"; how he writes in a "disciplined way" to make up for the "lack of inspiration", with an intense work of documentation, editing and continuous re-making; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his vocation and how "memory images" are the basis on which his stories are based.
The Spanish-American novelist, who acknowledged that "there is no way" to measure and know if books can change people's lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is a pure entertainment, a fleeting experience", Vargas Llosa pointed out, arguing that, on the contrary, "it has effects" and that it "makes people more anticonformist".
