A great admirer of Galdós's literature, Jose Luis Garci claims to have realized with this film "a dream of his childhood", and he believes he has to thank Esperanza Aguirre, who from the Community of Madrid had commissioned him three years before to shoot a commemorative film for the second centenary of 2 May in Madrid.
The 15 million budgets allocated entirely by the Community of Madrid represented a "unique opportunity" for Garci to recreate the appropriate settings and customs to portray a "stunned Spain that made the wrong choice of leader to fight for and the fact that the struggle for independence brought the people a huge development delay under Ferdinand VII's reign", Garci noted.
However, the director regrets not having received funding equal to that of Alatriste or Los fantasmas de Goya - more than twice as much as Sangre de mayo, so it was not possible to shoot some scenes provided by the scenography that he himself had signed together with Horacio Valcarcel, a collaborator of almost all his career.
This, for the director of Volver a empezar, has affected what is his usual work practice, the staging with the actors, with whom he often rehearses before shooting with those who will not be part of the cast, because he considers it "humiliating", considering that "part of the director's job is to go to the theater and the cinema to know what is happening in the sector in which he works".
Many of the performers, some of whom are part of the cast of Sangre de mayo, rehearse in front of his machine, as in the case of Michael Rell, Carlos Larranaga or Fernando Guillen Cuervo.
Four-time Oscar nominee - winning one - Garci believes that none of the three films nominated to represent Spain at the Hollywood Academy this year - his Sangre de mayo, Siete mesas de billar francés and, the last selected Los girasoles ciegos - represent the younger generation of Spanish cinema "which should be known instead".
Garci doesn't expect any prizes from this film.
"At first you think you are working for posterity, then you realize you are working only for prosperity, and at some point you are content to just make one more film", explains Garci after more than 30 years of career.
Isabel Bayon rediscovers the Sicilian essence of the dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sevillian dancer pays tribute to another dancer from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Firenze Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with her family to London.
She was a freestyle dancer and an oriental dancing specialist.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of women's emancipation, of the caliber of Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and she advocated for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two world wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have loved to have worked with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this character.
She says: "We don't pretend to tell her whole life, but to collect the spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "the butterfly dance" suggested a guajira, or "the snake dance" some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my way of dancing was also part of this aesthetic", she explains.
The staging features two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, as he does in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been his pupil.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy that he has agreed to work on my work and I feel very honored".
The set also includes the musical composition and guitarists like Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi by Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola by Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal companion of these artists who have been gods all around, and who have always had many hobbies".
The work also presents in some form the life of this woman who takes place in distant places, particularly for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, because, as usual, she resided in London.
"I wanted to remember her because I think she is one of the women who had a huge influence in a given historical period and now nobody remembers her and even less considers her work as something of value", says Bayon.
The show will begin today at 8:30 p.m. at the Lope de Vega Theater.
