Repeat drinkers will have to install the alcohol lock
The Home Office requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol levels to install a system in their car that prevents them from driving while intoxicated or if they don't blow into the device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Prosecutor General, which says it will be a one-year pilot project.
The aim of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since he will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
The initiative will be supported by the Directorate-General for Road Safety (DGT) and the Technological Institute for Motor Vehicle Safety (FITSA).
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers who are reported for drunk driving more than once then drive again.
The alcohol lock would prevent this, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher than permissible concentration of alcohol is detected.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the person sanctioned.
In this respect, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices reduce infringements by up to 65% in the first year of their introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, and I am sure that the Commission will be able to do so.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although it has already been experimentally introduced in some industrial and public vehicles.
The Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow on a PSOE initiative to install this system on school buses, as has already been done in France.
