Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I'm not talking about those who wake up very excited to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but those babies who talk while they're asleep.
The first time it happens, you're just gonna get scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somnolence.
It occurs with some frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure most of you have been told that you have talked in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with a high fever episode) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes these episodes are linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but not necessarily.
As mentioned earlier, it may be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
In any case, it is still a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may be that the person speaks with a very calm tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (yells, shouts, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it may be wise to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there is something that is causing the abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that it is a benign disorder so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situations).
What can be done, however, is to consider a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the baby too much before bedtime.
Offer quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that inspire fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleepwalkers show up, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful Advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's going on, and you'd interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember, if he appears very anxious and the episodes are frequent, it is best to see a doctor or to see where such great anxiety is coming from in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You're not getting anything, because he's asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you can hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming to say, so you must be very careful about interpreting the information and the conclusions it might lead to.
Never tell a child that you might ask him questions at night to learn his secrets.
Not even for fun.
Something like this causes a tremendous amount of distress.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing serious, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
