The Encounter - Blood is Safe Again
Hema-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Decary, had every reason to rejoice, for Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, he has regained the public's trust, which was seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood banks run by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980's.
In response to this tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent a similar disaster from occurring again.
While Judge Krever was slow to issue a report, some provinces set up a committee with the goal of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and the two territories.
When Héma-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the Quebec donation system, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the years, we have regained public trust", she says, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population in Quebec now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary believes that "trust is extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has been its president since 1998.
"And we had absolutely no idea that the disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when there is doubt and a serious illness could result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which manifests itself as a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, blood was refused to those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
Now, in recent years, it has been shown that this disease is transmitted without question by infected blood.
This incident thus showed us that the precautionary principle made sense".
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs), which allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors rather than antibodies against it, on which previous tests were based.
TANs have shortened the window from when a person has contracted the disease to when the first viruses can be detected in the bloodstream with our techniques, she explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and thus not being able to detect them has been greatly reduced.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before anyone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will be more than 24 years before a transfusion-transmitted HIV case is detected.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain one's health, says the head of the Héma-Québec board.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen will pop up in the system.
Not more than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant", Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also ensure that they are sufficient.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average make up only 3% of Quebecers who are eligible to donate".
However, all healthy persons over 18 years of age who meet the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where it is prevalent, they will be rejected for a period of up to a year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory that can meet the needs of hospitals.
The scarcity cases are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor group as they get older and can no longer donate.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but especially to keep them and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you can barely find an hour to donate blood", says Francine Décary, saddened.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which operates the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, is now rich in stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and plan to collect more than a thousand each year.
They should be proposed for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
