That "territory twice the size of France" is here, Quebec.
It is not only here, but it is in us", he insisted, as if to invoke a national founding myth.
The foundations of Quebec are rooted in its relationship with the North, he stressed: the gold rush in Abitibi, national engineering, James Bay.
"It's up to us, it's our future", he added, after a theatrical pause to contemplate the immense map behind him.
The north, which makes up 70% of Quebec, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the premier said at a press conference.
"It is a position traditionally held by all governments.
There is a border line on which no agreement has been reached for a long time and when the opportunity arises, I will reiterate that position on behalf of the government", he said.
He also said that "given climate change, we need to re-evaluate the North", referring to the Northwest Passage, which will be open all year round due to melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister considers occupying the territory a duty.
What about the locals, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very careful about this and that the project would be in their interests, especially those of young people.
Two former ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former PQ d'Ungava MP), have already started the consultation of some 30 communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) holds an important post, has started work.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a big meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "common visions will be provided"
The development of the North would also be based on the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be 'coordinated, orderly and respectful of the environment', he promised.
Jean Charest described this "project" as a continuum with that of the Liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
"Like the liberals before us, we are distinguished for turning challenges into new opportunities for growth and development".
