Free speech - The Orwellian discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was published by Mr Patrick J. Garver, deputy managing director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold mining company has filed a six million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, squandered publishing house with the intention of initiating a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a defamation suit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring ruin to anyone who dares to take a position contrary to theirs.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a considerable sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly odd weapons, against an army of lawyers funded from the mining company's practically bottomless pockets.
In these unequal arms wars, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensus settlement that will silence the opposition and scare anyone who dares to speak out again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it would have to present its view of the facts to the public.
Unlike in many countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are normally held by exchanging opinions and not by battering.
It would have been enough for the society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have much confidence in public opinion and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that very public is obvious?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even the denigrators have a say.
What Barrack Gold does not understand  or does not want to understand  is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Canada Black does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the light of what many perceive as a kind of muzzling (seeking the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum instructing them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver's surreal speech, the lawsuit brought by Barrack Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, which are indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are uncomfortable for the world's richest companies, or to file multiple lawsuits, who will?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, they could do it by following scientific norms like the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debate and disagreement and resolve conflict.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it is not seeking a transparent debate.
This is at the expense of the academic world, as well as the public debate itself in Canada, and it is time for governments to take steps to limit abuse lawsuits.
The operation - bailout for Wall Street  Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the top congressional leaders, representatives of both the Republican and Democratic parties, yesterday finally reached an agreement on the largest bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which aims to put a brake on the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
It includes checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to guarantee the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to limit the number of houses foreclosed for non-payment, and a right to inspect the salaries paid to managers of protected enterprises.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative Judd Gregg at the negotiating table announced the good news just minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an effective market agreement", said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
"Every decision was made in a way that safeguards the economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"It's the crux of the matter: if we hadn't acted this way, inestimable distress and disruption would have poured into the daily lives of Americans", said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The deadline agreed was for the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates for the US presidency, who joined the negotiations later, were quite supportive of the agreement, but did not hesitate to express their dissatisfaction at the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with adding provisions to the agreement, in particular the one allowing homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of state-owned enterprises.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary", he commented on the American TV screen.
When asked by another channel if he would vote for the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, said: "I'd like to look into the details, but I hope so".
"From what I've read, it's something we all have to digest and it'll allow us to move on".
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable", he said.
The 700 billion dollar plan aims to buy back with taxpayer money the dubious loans, risky assets and unsellable assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then extended to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and led to liquidity freezes and the dissolution of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of incumbent Republicans that blew the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems that we have come out of that blind alley since the Democrats accepted that the "toxic" assets of some struggling companies are only protected by the government, rather than bought.
In order to meet everyone's expectations, a provision was added to the Congress that if the government were to face losses over the next five years as a result of this program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for an initial payment of 250 billion, to which 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The $350 billion payment is expected to be ratified by a further vote in Congress.
In return for his help, Washington will get shares in the protected companies that will pay dividends if they make a profit and can sell them when the tide has turned.
Under the plan, the Federal Government will be able to delay foreclosure proceedings on mortgage loans and to set limits on the remuneration and severance payments paid to the directors of the companies involved.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives, and a vote in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is still not certain that their plan will be given the green light.
In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the bill, both on the Republican and Democratic sides.
"Obviously, Washington doesn't hear you", Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not taking advantage of the taxpayers.
