Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
The blue-eyed beauty was for a long time her ace in the hole, for others her weakness.
Had he gotten rid of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the enchanting smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and obvious talent would have driven him from that circle of powerful, consecrated, veritable sacred monsters.
What a consistency!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer, remains one of the last American film icons of the roaring twenties.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his play, certainly more fragile, but he too a spokesman for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
Mixed marriages often produce magical children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a mother of Hungarian origin.
From these European roots will spring one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, the ultimate quality mark.
Because he was a country full of safe-made men, a Pacific war veteran, proud of his combat, he studied drama at Yale in the early 1950s, then attended the Actor's Studio in New York before making his mark on theater, television and film.
The same civil rights activist was also the motor racing driver who finished second at the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, as well as a sex symbol, although part of a model couple since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
He's gone with the shadows of a reserved, discreet, busy star, allergic to show-business scandals, whose mystery will never be fully unveiled.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
This weekend's death of Paul Newman was a heartbreaking blow to film buffs, as his great characters fill the black screen of memory.
Over half a century of American cinema in full transformation is being re-proposed through his interpretations.
They confuse Butch Cassidy's charming cowboy (Buttch Cassidy, 1969) and that boy unable to desire the fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Roof adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
More recently, we remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that did not live up to its promise.
There are many other Paul Newman's in history.
Rocky Graziano, the boxer, the delinquent, the tormented, the violent, the unforgettable in Robert Wise's Someone Loves Me, a role originally intended for James Dean and resumed after his death, which officially launched Newman in 1956.
That nice villain in the excellent Stangata, Oscar for best picture in 1973.
Bitter and vengeful billiard player in The Spy, magnificent film by Robert Rossen (1961), The Color of Money by Martin Scorsese, which won him in 1987 the only Oscar out of 9 nominations.
That face over the years, it was his.
He's at it again.
The ages follow one another through its path.
Young people know him best for the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), in which he played Reggie Dunlop, the coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, by the Coen brothers.
The circle was closed with a final role as the Irish mob's godfather in It Was My Father in 2003.
Unlike most of the film legends who soon left the business, Newman would remain in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its pomp, partying and concessions.
Bertrand Tavernier, a French filmmaker, called it, with a touch of irony, "a living challenge to underplaying", judging his performance exaggerated.
The profession was not always a game for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom roles seemed to fall like manna from the sky.
However, he often preferred the role of the outcast to that of the young actor: neurotic, alcoholic, dead or desperate characters, of whom he expressed disdain and rebellion with his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown nuances of his true, modest sensibility.
Jennifer's 1968 debut (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with her wife Joanne Woodward in the title role, traced a subtle female portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated to him in 1984 the film Harry and Son, a discreet and sad film.
Among the countless tributes poured on Newman yesterday, his great friend and old comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had acted together in The Stangata and Butch Cassidy) said with infinite sadness, "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity and love of life, two great traits of the late actor.
Beyond a legendary career, a great civil rights activist, environmentalist, independent filmmaker, a contender against the Hollywood drift, is thus extinguished.
We'll have seen her face stand out on bottles of vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging it a tasteless choice, though born as a gag.
The proceeds from those sales were, however, intended for his Foundation for Children in Need.
Newman, instead of settling for his myth, chose to commit to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter that said, "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his good star.
It was a privilege to be there".
And it was just as privileged for us to follow the path of such a clear and generous American artist.
Model citizen, then, and much more.
What was produced in the Zuschlag & Associates invoice factory?
The hearing in the criminal case against János Zuschlag and Associates will be held shortly, on 8 October.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed as part of a criminal association that caused considerable damage, and other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Prosecutor, the money obtained from the tendering process was used for private purposes and they often certified the activities by means of false invoices.
The State and municipal money, totalling 65 million guilders, has partly ended up in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the methodology disclosed by the investigating authorities, they withdrew the money obtained from the invitations to tender on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the blocks of invoices were purchased at the market in Józsefváros, while the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue invoices, it was established, among other things, during the trip through the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession, he had to choose between boarding houses and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for consumption, and the invoices were then prepared to be sent to the invitations to tender, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
Many of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri, who, according to our information, mainly drafted the reports necessary to obtain the funding.
One of the choices of Lados' "study trip" was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Partners in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 people from Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But so many people, the restaurant owner says, would not all enter the place at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, is full of errors of form and content.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay there, however, the bill listed 130 guests.
But the imaginative invoicers went too far in pointing out that Pigal Kft., also a catering company, did not even have the documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá in its accounts, according to information given to the judicial authorities.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when he was called to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he immediately knew that they were fake documents.
"On the stamp the name and VAT number of our company were in the wrong place".
He added: 'In addition to the formal reasons, the fact that the bill says 100 people were accommodated, when in total they have 11 rooms and there are not so many beds, was not relevant either.'
Plus, the bill was for catering and their restaurant hasn't been open in a while.
The diligent invoicers did not bother to find out that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only arranges trips abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice that they would pay for travel in cash to Hungary, which was not in line with the company's invoicing practice.
Moreover, as demonstrated during the investigation, the invoice also included VAT, while the activity of travel to countries outside the European Union is exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favour of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the VAT on the services offered by the company was 15% and not 25% as indicated on the invoices, and the hotel employees only issued printed invoices, while the manufactured invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the 'issuers' have ruined other invoices, in the case of one company they have indicated as their activity the transport of goods by road, as is clear from the proceedings of the Public Prosecutor's Office, an activity which was not carried out by the company originally founded for investment advice.
Furthermore, because of formal defects - the case was in the form of a non-compliant invoice, a false stamp - the invoices issued in favour of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont were found to be false.
The same was true in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sporting Ground, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters also failed to notice that HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület had lunch there in 2001, which is why the liquidation officer of the company, according to our information, denied that he had issued that invoice.
They've been issuing invoices knowingly.
Another group of invoice issuers is those who were aware that they were issuing dummy invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation has issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták in favour of the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért of almost 4 million guilders.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fake invoices.
Biogate Kft, which is currently in liquidation, also cooperated with Zuschlag and its partners and in 2003 provided invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület, which did not involve any real economic activity.
Nor was there any movement of money because the bills prepared were then returned, but the associations forgot to mention this in their documents.
The following group of invoice companies includes those who are related to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorized by the Managing Director of Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, which deals in fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 relating to the sale of computer equipment, worth about 18 million guilders.
According to the investigation data, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, purchased these invoices.
The CEO of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov allegedly forwarded the documents concerning the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation to having issued invoices in the company's name to Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the countervailing amount was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov, Romanian masons founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
However, none of the firms were actually operating, because according to the defendant they had not received work.
The companies did however benefit from the fact that, at the request of the co-accused lawyer, Mr Zsolt Szente, draftsman of the company's articles of association, invoices were issued on behalf of the companies to the associations linked to Zuschlag, namely Atlas and Y-Generáció.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov issued 15 invoices to the various institutions for a total value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution believes Kubatov pocketed 10% of the amounts shown on the invoices, plus VAT.
The man also used Szi-Beri Bt. to issue dummy invoices, fabricated for Biztos Pont's tender.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a bid for the public utility of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 guilders each but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the invitation.
To prevent this from being revealed, they submitted to the TMA five bogus invoices received by Works Team Kft.
These invoices were found during a search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will probably report on the production of invoices, as they have already done in the prosecution.
However, the most interesting thing might be if the number one defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to lift the veil on everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything at length, he has not yet done so.
We must see if it is in his interest, it could also be that the Socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in return for compensation of 50 million guilders, a large part of the damage - would be willing to make the sacrifice.
Mr Zuschlag could have been offended for the moment, since his requests for easing of his prison conditions, i.e. granting him house arrest, have so far not been granted.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the Commission's proposals are implemented.
The psychology of overbidden: Why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neuroscientists and economists at New York University have managed to uncover the neuroeconomic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to be left behind in a competition like the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay even a higher price.
Research has sought to trace the neural pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system by experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction while using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) they examined the active areas of the brains of the people in the experiment.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the essential element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex becomes intensively active when you lose the game.
This area of the brain, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-gratification" mechanism.
So the researchers say the price increase is explained by the scanning of the veer reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists in the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this survey, three groups bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
Another group, besides this one, was promised that if they won, they would receive another prize of $15.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the group members would lose the money if they lost at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasized as winning, while the other group was emphasized as losing.
Testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "losing" group were willing to bet higher than the control or "winning" group.
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These have so far explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the neurological imaging methods have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients is 100,000, of whom only 7,000 are being treated, because many patients are unaware that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name for infectious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and hysteria, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. infected water and food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
It is useful for travellers to get vaccinated against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine for C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After yellow spots form on the skin and whites of the eyes, the stool becomes clear and the urine dark, healing occurs within two to three weeks.
A million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason is that only one in ten people is estimated to receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences. If left untreated, it can cause cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not know they have the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
So prevention and regular medical checks are very important.
This disease is much more common than average in three groups: those who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus today is 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worthwhile to consult your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
If the disease is recognized early, it can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, and the infectious power can be stopped and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
World Hepatitis Day is observed on 30 September, first organized in 2004 by the World Hepatitis Association.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, its causes and early detection.
Do people who believe in God feel less pain?
A recent survey found that religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment examining the effect of faith in God on the feeling of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were electrocuted while all were looking at a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Through the human brain exploration technique, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling pain.
The test is the first in a series of studies involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from the university.
The test went exactly as follows: An instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassopheratus and the Lady with the Hermitage by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time frame received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while looking at either the religious painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "secure", as if "someone was taking care" of them and "they were reassured and filled with peace".
When they looked at the religious-themed image, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they had the Leonardo painting in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the test, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image that has a strong effect even on atheists, but the right image must be found.
"We have to look for an image that they have very positive feelings about, like a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it does change our personality", Wright added.
After the excellent results, the only question remains: If a painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect might it have on pain control?
Would a vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say you are
On their 10th birthday, Google can claim to be in people's pockets as much as it is in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, what clinics they go to and what they are interested in.
But that, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the firm's directors, is not enough.
As for the skeptics who compare it to the Orwellian nightmare, they don't see the essence of Web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and this is necessary to adhere to the original goal of the founders of Google which was: "let's put all the information in the world in one system!".
According to the Google executive interviewed, the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, is still in the beginning of being able to manage all information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What am I doing tomorrow?" or "What would be the right job for me?" but software cannot answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their Internet searches, exactly what words they are searching for are recorded, from which IP address they are searching for and on which page they stop after searching.
Through the Personalized Search launched two years ago, users can store their browsing history, can look at what they have searched and clicked, these will then in the long run generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our preferences declared and registered previously.
What if my data is used against me, if they look at what I'm doing? - users worried about Google's data monopoly ask.
In most cases, the reaction of netizens is caused by fear of the potential power of the company, not guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against the power.
One fact is confirmed, however, namely that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing protects the personal rights of internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times was the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
But concerned Internet users for their personal rights were relieved in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even after that, Google cannot be forced under any provision of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully cracked almost 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain the search lists of individual users and the entire list of web pages and keywords from two months ago.)
Google's assessment is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid to provide their personal data to Google because they believe that this will affect their private sphere and privacy by starting to use its services and rise with the rebellion of multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of computer enthusiasts, activists and users in many countries see them as the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, Microsoft, which is being dismissed as a conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both are fighting for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet, which implies one of the most frequently repeated keywords in recent years, Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the essence is the same: showing ourselves.
A young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them to other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of these can be inserted into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which his latest photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous examples of how the girl, seeing the series of pictures taken in the morning by her friends, can easily find out who her mean boyfriend spent the night with or how a company can fire an employee for writing a sincere opinion about the company's top management. One thing is certain, the concept of privacy has now been completely reconsidered.
The online life is about showing yourself and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis behind the behavior of young people.
Anyone who wants to hide something or just wants to avoid Google's monopoly can do so (starting with Scroogle using Google's search engine but at the same time not leaving any traces).
There are a lot of people who don't register on community pages on purpose to avoid being found, and Google's online applications, from word processing to image management and news gathering, can be replaced with alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and that don't make up our best profile yet.
The public is not secretly waiting for the moment when Google will pull its claws out.
Currently the company with its 156 billion dollars worth is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising spaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, services introduced in record time cause instead big problems not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development companies.
However, critics find some alarming points alongside this: the company's top management, for example, completely rejected the employees' protest after doubling the company's daycare fee, deemed it too expensive to repeatedly cater to the employees' daily pleasure, all of which is dwarfed by the fact that in 2006 Google bowed its head to the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter all results that offend the good taste and interests of the Chinese regime.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it is usable, but one thing is for sure, that the predictable problems of the next months and years will move the world to a point: while some believe that Google's project of scanning and archiving books and magazines will take on such proportions that the company will soon be in front of the US Supreme Court, others are afraid of the Health system, in fact in this we can create our own health profile with our reports, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the famous short story Scroogled by Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, where a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
