The Warsaw Stock Exchange has made an offer to buy the Prague Stock Exchange.
The Warsaw Stock Exchange offered EUR 200 million, or about CZK 5 billion, for the purchase of 100% of the shares listed on the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed the offer made by the Poles despite the fact that the Czechs had previously ruled out the Warsaw Stock Exchange as a possible buyer of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason for the exclusion is the fact that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is state-owned.
The 99% of the shares are held by the Polish State, which intends to sell more than 60% of its shares within a few months.
The Czech financial newspaper E15 says that the Polish bid represents the highest figure ever submitted for the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the Transatlantic Nasdaq Stock Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and the German Stock Exchange have so far submitted an offer.
Petr Koblic, director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the worst owner of all the parties involved and he did not rule out that this could lead to the closure of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
Market experts estimate the value of the Prague Stock Exchange at 5-10 billion crowns.
The shareholders' agreement was that almost 90% of the shares would be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is Patria Finance with a share of almost 25%, followed by Česká Spořitelna Bank with 14.7% and Tiger Holding Four S. a.r.l. with 13.5%
The economic crisis as seen by European newspapers
The main European newspapers in their Tuesday commentaries on the international economic crisis already speak of "a second 9/11".
The global financial disaster was caused by the US president, La Repubblica accuses, who was unable to rally his party behind a hastily passed law designed to remedy a desperate situation.
Instead of a second Pearl Harbor, as billionaire superfinance mogul Warren Buffett said, it would be more accurate to talk about a second 9/11.
Even a section of the Madrid press sees Washington as a scapegoat.
According to El Mundo, the lack of American political leadership has pushed the world economy to the brink.
The danger of the collapse of the American financial system is growing and the whole world will suffer as a result.
Bush's plan was not perfect but as a result of the congressional vote there is a danger that Washington will not offer a political means of managing the crisis.
The world economy is suspended in the air, just as the greatest transformation in the history of capitalism is taking place.
The threat is no longer something to be ignored - mentions the Tages-Anzeiger of Geneva.
Some states today can still offer a bailout doughnut to faltering financial institutions and with taxpayers' money can save them from bankruptcy.
But if more and more banks collapse like a domino effect then neither the financial means nor new improvised solutions will be enough.
