The intelligent machine imitates the hornet's flight
What better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than by mimicking obstacle sensors found in nature?
Like the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, hornets gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic idea for how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic mini-car with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
"The bees flying form their own oval personal space that really looks like our protective shield", explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development at the exhibition.
The bee's eyesight is important, with a 300-degree view in every direction.
Engineers have tapped into the laser telemetry idea to mimic the bee's visual function.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor which immediately turns it into a collision avoidance command.
In a fraction of a second, the robot senses the obstacle and then, imitating the bee's movements, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the crash.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, is entirely instinctive.
"If it weren't for this, the robot car wouldn't be able to react quickly to avoid collisions", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology is the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to mirror what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deflection cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering wheels.
So instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
BR23C is powered by lighter, high-energy polymer lithium batteries, which means they last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh said that the instantaneity of intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some input in a few seconds and react.
No need to memorize them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
You don't need a gigabyte or megabyte of memory.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions which, they expect Nissan to install on production vehicles within 10 years.
A further possibility of application is the integration with the GPS satellite navigation system, which by avoiding obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
