In both the United States and Europe the crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator of long-incubated phenomena which in the new climate are solidifying and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualisation, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of State-sovereignty in relation to a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which have, yes, close links with the outside world, but which are primarily concerned to a very large extent with the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one State.
Which immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: namely how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, by the way, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of the picture or to have little say: the European Union, divided as usual between different interests and different national strategies, is a clear example of this.
And so it is from the governments of each individual country that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you come to a crisis only the countries have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources to try to put things right.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, under certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization will ever have to an equal extent.
This new emphasis on the national-statutory element is also in perfect harmony with the growing importance which recent economic developments tend to attach to a factor closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the net, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the intangible, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to deal increasingly with those very little intangible things which are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look at it, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are still absolutely bound to a limited space, to a territory.
So the one who happens to be the ruler of it certainly has a lot more cards than the one who is not, the one who has the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second news, which, however, presages a break.
When you say Territory, State, Government, you inevitably say Politics, and therefore Leadership.
The economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena in this respect.
On the one hand, the recognition of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the need for someone who can take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, there is a wave of discrediting of existing leadership, economic leadership, which has proved so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together with something even deeper and somewhat disturbing: a discredit, an impatience, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
It is a question of the fact that the European Parliament has not yet been able to adopt the necessary measures to ensure that the European Parliament is able to take part in the negotiations.
The demand for leadership, in short, underground feeds a broad but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "electoral revolts" or sudden changes in collective moods of recent times, from the rise of conservatism in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, some would say, are making it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not today taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating, increasing, potentially agitating to an excess.
In the face of all this, it would be frankly an exaggeration to call a 'mass revolt' on the agenda.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not for nothing.
