Open Office, here is the third edition of the anti-Microsoft package.
It's the day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more well-known Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work by volunteer developers, with SUN Microsystem as its backbone, the new Open Office is presented to the public with several new features: the welcome screen and the revised and less spartan interface, as well as more substantial features such as native compatibility for the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Attention is also paid to interoperability with the Office 2007 suite, Open Office is able to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Some specific features of some modules are interesting, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example to send them by e-mail, or the ability to import PDF files into the graphics processing module, preserving the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front, you can create "hybrid PDF" documents, which combine typical Adobe graphics with elements of a spreadsheet or a text processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received several improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet you can intervene in multiple hands between different users, avoiding conflicts over changes, in the text editor, each collaborator is assigned a color in the comments for better recognition during revision.
Some companies are also working to bring some OpenOffice functionality to the Web (on the cloud, on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they should release the final result.
The Italian version is available for download at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and has been added to the English version that was on mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD can also be sent to your home or workplace on request.
And if the theme of free of charge can be a trigger for the spread in homes, it is precisely in the business field that the Open Office suite tries the big bet, already being able to count on several projects carried out in public administration and schools.
There is also a shortage of companies offering training, consultancy and assistance services which are ideal for small and mediumsized enterprises, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the corresponding video writing of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for the emulating presentations of Powerpoint; Dbase, as in the case of the most famous Access is the program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, is finally the graphic module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that we are now at almost 3.6 million, with the release of the new version it is likely that we can even exceed the expected figure.
