The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the emergence of large multi-screen cinemas in the outskirts and the consequent death of single-screen cinemas in the central areas of cities, is one of those events which seem inevitable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
"It's like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a road and many emotions", says the director of New Cinema Paradiso, the film that won Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes Jury 20 years ago, and which told the story of the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for a way of living cinema lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by ANAC, the main association of the exhibitors, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the main losers are the cinemas in the main cities: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna is the region most affected by the closures, with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
