When the energy comes from the waves, the big ones come in.
It's an endless field, covering over 70% of the planet's surface and now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources they've set their sights on, and now they're trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of deriving energy from the movement of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in the 1980's, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now environmental concerns and the new rise in oil are giving the industry a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by offshore wind farms.
This would be twice as much as is currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossal in the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy and among these companies have always been committed to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies", a spokesman for a company affiliated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering working with us".
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit from the US Energy Commission for a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is a good sign, especially when you consider that the United States is still drilling for oil in Alaska and that President Bush recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are taking the sea energy route and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be perfected.
Experts say it is a technology in its infancy, partly because marine energy is not without its environmental impact.
For now, plants like the one in Portugal or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to be causing major problems for the ecosystem.
But large-scale energy production requires technologies with a greater environmental impact.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The wave force that moves the buoys up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through undersea cables.
There are four such plants currently in the planning stages, pending federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water when there are tides causes the turbine blades to spin, creating a rotational motion that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to use the power.
After the waves, the tides.
The potential of tides is of particular interest, say the Electric Power Research Institute.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
It is on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that face the coast, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and are planning to invest up to $35 million in 2009.
